    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "\nHLH is a rare syndrome of marked immune activation that can mimic sepsis. HLH may be triggered by infection, neoplasms, autoimmune disorders, or genetic mutations.5\nLCH is a clonal proliferation of mononuclear phagocytic cells (histiocytes). LCH can be local and asymptomatic, or it can involve multiple organs. It can present as SIRS and even shock.6\n,\n7 The most common sites of involvement are the skin, bones, lungs, liver, spleen, teeth, gums, and central nervous system (manifesting as diabetes insipidus).6\n\u2013\n8\nReports have linked LCH and HLH. The pathogenesis is still unknown, but it is suspected that macrophage activation through T-cell activation and cytokine release plays an important role in the pathophysiology.9\n\n",
